    "summarizer": {
      "general_reader_takeaway": "This paper aims to show that stars and gas clouds orbiting the center of our galaxy can be explained by a dense ball of dark-matter particles rather than a conventional supermassive black hole. The review board was unable to evaluate the scientific content because the automated system that fetched the paper captured only a website navigation bar \u2014 no actual text or equations were retrieved, almost certainly due to a journal paywall. One reviewer produced an elaborate technical commentary despite having access to the same empty stub, which the other two reviewers independently identified as fabricated. The single most important caveat is that this review is effectively a review of a missing document; the paper must be re-fetched from a preprint server or via institutional access before any scientific judgment is possible.",
      "reviewer": "claude",
      "technical_takeaway": "The review bundle contains only 305 characters of Oxford University Press HTML navigation boilerplate; the paper body was not retrieved. All three reviewers confirmed this fatal defect. One reviewer (Codex) nonetheless produced a detailed multi-section review citing specific line numbers, section identifiers, table values, and quantitative results (e.g., log B_1,2 = 10.1; G2 semimajor axis 0.464 vs. 0.450 arcsec; fermion masses 56 keV and 300 keV) that cannot originate from the available 305-character stub. The other two reviewers independently flagged these claims as hallucinated, likely drawn from Codex's training-data exposure to the RAR (Arg\u00fcelles\u2013Rueda\u2013Ruffini) fermionic dark-matter research program. Treating Codex's notes as provisional and conditional on their provenance being verified, the residual technical concerns are: (1) a potential internal inconsistency between an abstract claim of less than 1 per cent orbital-parameter differences and tabulated G-object data showing differences exceeding 5 per cent for G2 and G5 periods; (2) Bayes factors that appear unreproducible because prior supports for the 12-dimensional RAR parameter space are reportedly not specified; (3) under-documented MCMC convergence diagnostics; (4) G-object model comparison that conditions on fixed S2 maximum-likelihood potentials rather than marginalizing over central-potential uncertainty. Domain-knowledge objections from Claude include the need for any fermionic dark-matter model to satisfy EHT Sgr A* 2022 photon-ring imaging constraints and the GRAVITY-measured S2 Schwarzschild precession \u2014 neither of which could be verified from the bundle."
